\f1 \cf2 \strokec2 This is from r/pennystocks, and the poster (Confident-Web-7118) is making a cure-fraction argument for a clinical trial \'97 looks like it's for\'a0
\f2\b REGAL
\f1\b0 \'a0(probably imetelstat or a similar AML trial). Let me give you an honest assessment.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 What they get right
\f1\b0 \
The core logic is sound: if you fix two event count anchors (60 at month 46, 72 at month 58) and test standard parametric survival families, models without a cure fraction will tend to overshoot future event accumulation. That's a legitimate observation. The event velocity deceleration chart is also a reasonable way to visualize hazard behavior over time.\

\f2\b Where it gets shaky
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 "99.99% probability of success"
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 this is the tell. No model fitted to summary-level public data (two event count snapshots) can generate that kind of precision. That's not a statistical claim, it's a rhetorical one.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The cure-fraction inference is overdetermined.
\f1\b0 \'a0Fitting 6 model families to 2 constraints will almost always find a solution. That's not model validation, it's curve fitting with nearly infinite degrees of freedom. You need out-of-sample predictive power to distinguish models.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Biological cap argument is weak.
\f1\b0 \'a0Saying AML CR2 has a 6-12 month biological cap and therefore long-tail survivors\'a0
\f3\i must
\f1\i0 \'a0be cured is a non-sequitur. Unmeasured heterogeneity (frailty), patient selection, and supportive care variability can all produce apparent tails without a true cure fraction.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The chart shows model agreement, not model validation.
\f1\b0 \'a0All 6 models roughly tracking each other through observed data doesn't confirm the cure fraction \'97 it just means they were all calibrated to the same anchors.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 Bottom line
\f1\b0 \
It's a sophisticated-sounding retail investor post, not rigorous biostatistics. The event deceleration observation is real and worth noting. The leap to "99.99% success probability" is not defensible from the methodology described. Anyone seriously analyzing this trial should look at the actual KM curves, protocol-specified primary endpoint, and DSMB interim guidance \'97 not Reddit curve-fitting.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

