\f1 \cf2 \strokec2 Great question \'97 it comes from first principles of probability, not from any paper.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 The setup
\f1\b0 \
In a mixture cure model you assume the trial population is made up of\'a0
\f2\b two latent subgroups
\f1\b0 :\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls33\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 A fraction\'a0
\f2\b \uc0\u960 
\f1\b0 \'a0who are "cured" \'97 their hazard is zero, they will never have the event\
\ls33\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 A fraction\'a0
\f2\b (1 - \uc0\u960 )
\f1\b0 \'a0who are "susceptible" \'97 they will eventually have the event, their survival follows some distribution\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 You don't know which group any individual patient is in \'97 that's the latent part.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 Deriving S(t) from first principles
\f1\b0 \
The overall survival probability at time t is just the\'a0
\f2\b law of total probability
\f1\b0 :\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 P(survive past t) = P(survive | cured) \'d7 P(cured)\
                  + P(survive | susceptible) \'d7 P(susceptible)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 Plugging in:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls34\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 P(survive past t | cured) =\'a0
\f2\b 1
\f1\b0 \'a0for all t, because cured patients never die from the disease\
\ls34\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 P(cured) =\'a0
\f2\b \uc0\u960 
\f1\b0 \
\ls34\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 P(survive past t | susceptible) =\'a0
\f2\b S_susceptible(t)
\f1\b0 , whatever parametric form you choose (Weibull, Log-Normal, etc.)\
\ls34\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 P(susceptible) =\'a0
\f2\b (1 - \uc0\u960 )
\f1\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 So:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 S(t) = 1 \'d7 \uc0\u960  + S_susceptible(t) \'d7 (1 - \u960 )\
     = \uc0\u960  + (1 - \u960 ) \'d7 S_susceptible(t)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 Why this produces a plateau
\f1\b0 \
As t 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  \uc0\u8734 , susceptible patients all eventually die, so S_susceptible(\u8734 ) 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  0:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 S(\uc0\u8734 ) = \u960  + (1 - \u960 ) \'d7 0 = \u960 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 The curve never goes below \uc0\u960  \'97 that's the plateau you see in the Phase 2 KM curves. The height of that plateau\'a0
\f3\i is
\f1\i0 \'a0the cure fraction, which is why you can read \uc0\u960  directly off a KM curve if follow-up is long enough.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 And the Weibull choice for S_susceptible
\f1\b0 \
You could use any survival distribution there. Weibull is convenient because:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls35\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Two parameters (scale \uc0\u955 , shape k) \'97 easy to fit from median OS and one shape assumption\
\ls35\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 k > 1 gives increasing hazard over time, which is appropriate for AML where risk isn't constant\
\ls35\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Reduces to exponential when k = 1\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 That's the only modeling assumption layered on top of the pure probability derivation.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

