\f1 \cf2 \strokec2 The full technical name is a\'a0
\f2\b parametric mixture cure model
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 sometimes also called a\'a0
\f2\b cure fraction model
\f1\b0 \'a0or\'a0
\f2\b split population model
\f1\b0 .\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 Breaking down the terminology
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls36\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Parametric
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 because you're assuming a specific distributional form for the susceptible subpopulation (Weibull in this case), rather than leaving it nonparametric like a standard KM estimator\
\ls36\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Mixture
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 because the population is modeled as a mixture of two latent subgroups (cured + susceptible), weighted by \uc0\u960  and (1-\u960 )\
\ls36\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Cure
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 because the cured fraction has a degenerate survival distribution with S(\uc0\u8734 ) = 1, i.e. they never experience the event\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 Related names you'll see in the literature
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls37\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Mixture cure model (MCM)
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 the most common term in biostatistics papers\
\ls37\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Two-component mixture model
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 more general framing\
\ls37\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Bounded cumulative hazard model
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 because the cumulative hazard H(t) is bounded rather than going to infinity\
\ls37\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Split population model
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 common in econometrics and criminology for the same math applied to recidivism\
\ls37\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Long-term survivor model
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 older clinical literature term\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 The alternative formulation
\f1\b0 \
There's also a\'a0
\f2\b non-mixture cure model
\f1\b0 \'a0(sometimes called the\'a0
\f2\b promotion time cure model
\f1\b0 ) due to Yakovlev & Tsodikov, where the cure fraction emerges from a biological mechanism (number of metastatic cells) rather than being directly parameterized. The math looks different but produces similar shaped curves. You'll see both in the AML/immunotherapy literature.\
For GPS specifically, the mixture formulation is the more natural choice because you have a mechanistic story (HLA 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  immune response 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  cure) that maps directly onto the \uc0\u960  parameter.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

