\f1 \cf2 \strokec2 Sure. Let me build it up from scratch.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 The fundamental problem with standard survival models in this context
\f1\b0 \
A standard Weibull or Cox model assumes that\'a0
\f3\i everyone
\f1\i0 \'a0will eventually have the event (death) \'97 it's just a question of when. The cumulative hazard H(t) 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  \uc0\u8734  as t 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  \uc0\u8734 , meaning S(t) 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  0 for everyone eventually.\
But look at the Phase 2 Figure 5 \'97 the responder KM curve stops declining and flattens. That can't happen in a standard survival model. It implies some patients will\'a0
\f2\b never
\f1\b0 \'a0die from AML, at least within any observable timeframe. A standard model fundamentally can't represent that.\
\

\f2\b The mixture cure model's solution
\f1\b0 \
Split the population into two groups at the outset:\

\f2\b Group 1 \'97 Cured (fraction \uc0\u960 )
\f1\b0 \'a0These patients have zero hazard from the disease. Their survival function is just 1 for all time. They'll die eventually from something else, but not AML CR2.\

\f2\b Group 2 \'97 Susceptible (fraction 1-\uc0\u960 )
\f1\b0 \'a0These patients will eventually relapse and die. Their survival follows a standard parametric distribution \'97 Weibull in our case.\
The key insight is you\'a0
\f2\b don't know which group any patient is in
\f1\b0 \'a0when you observe them. A patient alive at month 60 could be cured, or just a long-tailed susceptible patient who hasn't relapsed yet. The model has to account for that uncertainty.\
\

\f2\b The math
\f1\b0 \
Because you can't observe group membership directly, you use the law of total probability across both groups:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 S(t) = P(alive at t | cured) \'d7 P(cured)\
     + P(alive at t | susceptible) \'d7 P(susceptible)\
\
     = 1 \'d7 \uc0\u960   +  S_weibull(t) \'d7 (1 - \u960 )\
\
     = \uc0\u960  + (1 - \u960 ) \'d7 S_weibull(t)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 Where S_weibull(t) = exp(-(t/\uc0\u955 )^k) handles the susceptible subpopulation.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 What each parameter controls
\f1\b0 \
