\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u960 
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 the height of the long-run plateau. Directly readable off a KM curve with long enough follow-up\
\ls38\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u955 
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 the Weibull scale, derived from the median OS of the\'a0
\f3\i non-cured
\f1\i0 \'a0patients\
\ls38\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 k
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 the Weibull shape, controls whether hazard is increasing (k>1), constant (k=1), or decreasing (k<1). For AML we use k>1 because hazard increases over time\
