\f2\b \cf2 What the curve looks like
\f1\b0 \
Early timepoints \'97 S_weibull(t) is still close to 1, so the curve behaves almost like a normal survival curve and both groups look similar.\
Middle timepoints \'97 S_weibull(t) decays rapidly as susceptible patients die. The curve drops steeply.\
Late timepoints \'97 S_weibull(t) 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  0, so the whole expression converges to just \uc0\u960 . The curve flattens into a plateau at exactly the cure fraction.\
That's the signature you saw in Figure 5 \'97 the red responder curve going flat around month 40-65 at ~57%.\
\

\f2\b How \uc0\u960  was estimated for GPS specifically
\f1\b0 \
Rather than fitting \uc0\u960  statistically from patient-level data (which we don't have), we derived it from the biological chain:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 \uc0\u960  = P(HLA-A*02:01+) \'d7 P(CD8 response | HLA+) \'d7 P(cured | responder)\
  = 0.45 \'d7 0.86 \'d7 0.575\
  \uc0\u8776  22%  +  small residual terms  \u8776   26%\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 Each of those three probabilities came from a different source \'97 HLA population literature, Phase 2 immunologic correlate data, and Figure 5 respectively. That's what makes the estimate grounded rather than arbitrary.\
