\f2\b \cf2 Why the long peptides are clever
\f1\b0 \
This is actually the key design insight. A 9-mer peptide is highly HLA-restricted \'97 it only fits one or two specific HLA grooves. But the long peptides (18-23 amino acids) are too big to bind directly to any HLA molecule. Instead they get taken up by antigen presenting cells, chopped into multiple shorter fragments intracellularly, and those fragments can fit into many different HLA grooves. Peptide 122 includes a known CD8+ epitope (WT1A: 126\'96134), and when this mutated peptide was embedded within the longer 122 CD4+ epitope, a robust CD4 and CD8 WT1-specific T-cell response could be induced simultaneously.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/galinpepimut-s"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs18 \cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \cb13 ScienceDirect\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 The bottom line for your model
\f1\b0 \
This is why the 91% immune response rate across HLA types in the MM data makes biological sense \'97 it's not one peptide binding one HLA allele, it's four peptides generating a combinatorial library of fragments that collectively cover a very large fraction of the HLA diversity in any given population. The HLA-A*02:01\'a0restriction applies specifically to the short WT1-A1 peptide's direct CD8+ route, but the long peptides create parallel pathways that bypass that restriction entirely.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

