\f2\b \cf2 How this changes the cure fraction derivation
\f1\b0 \
Our original model was too narrowly anchored on HLA-A*02:01\'a0because we treated it as the primary gating factor. The correct framing has two components that partially overlap:\

\f2\b Component 1 \'97 HLA-A*02:01+ patients
\f1\b0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 P(cured | HLA-A*02:01+)\
= P(CD8 response via WT1-A1) \'d7 P(cured | CD8 responder)\
= 0.86 \'d7 0.575\
= ~49%\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 These patients get both the direct CD8+ route AND the long peptide routes simultaneously \'97 the strongest possible immune activation.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 Component 2 \'97 HLA-A*02:01- patients
\f1\b0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 P(cured | HLA-A*02:01-)\
= P(response via long peptide processing) \'d7 P(cured | responder)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 This is where it gets genuinely uncertain. The MM data showed 91% immune response across all HLA types \'97 but that's a different disease, different patient population, and different immune context. For AML CR2 the equivalent number is unknown.\
A conservative estimate for the long-peptide-only response rate in HLA-A
\f3\i 02:01- patients is probably\'a0
\f4\b 50-65%
\f3\b0 , and their cure fraction conditional on responding is probably lower than A
\f1\i0 02:01+ patients because they lack the direct CD8+ killing pathway. Maybe\'a0
\f2\b 25-35%
\f1\b0 \'a0of responders in this group achieve durable remission.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

