\f2\b \cf2 What the numbers actually are
\f1\b0 \
There's a distinction between:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls51\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Allele frequency
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 the proportion of chromosomes in the population carrying the allele. This is what population genetics databases report. For European populations this is ~27%\
\ls51\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Carrier frequency
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 the proportion of\'a0
\f3\i individuals
\f1\i0 \'a0who have at least one copy (heterozygous or homozygous). This is what matters clinically because you only need one copy to present peptides\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 The conversion from allele frequency to carrier frequency uses Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 Carrier frequency = 1 - (1 - allele frequency)\'b2\
                  = 1 - (1 - 0.27)\'b2\
                  = 1 - (0.73)\'b2\
                  = 1 - 0.533\
                  = ~47%\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 So where did 45% come from specifically
\f1\b0 \
Honestly it was a rounded approximation I used based on the HWE calculation from the European allele frequency, plus a rough acknowledgment that REGAL's trial population isn't purely European. The Brazilian paper we found earlier cited ~45% for North Americans and Europeans directly, which converged on the same number.\
\

\f2\b What you should actually use
\f1\b0 \
The more rigorous approach would be to look at REGAL's specific enrollment demographics. AML CR2 patients skew:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls52\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Elderly (median age probably 60s)\
\ls52\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Predominantly White given where trials enroll\
\ls52\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 US and European sites primarily\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 If REGAL's demographics are say 85% White, 8% Hispanic, 5% Black, 2% Asian, the weighted carrier frequency would be:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 0.85 \'d7 0.47  (European)\
+ 0.08 \'d7 0.37  (Hispanic)\
+ 0.05 \'d7 0.22  (African American)\
+ 0.02 \'d7 0.13  (Asian)\
= 0.400 + 0.030 + 0.011 + 0.003\
= ~44%\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 Which is where the 45% figure comes from \'97 it's a population-weighted HWE estimate, not a directly measured number from REGAL. The actual number would require seeing the trial's demographic table, which would be in the full publication or an SEC filing.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 The important caveat for the model
\f1\b0 \
This is actually one of the more solid parameters in the whole model \'97 the HLA-A*02:01\'a0carrier frequency in a predominantly White elderly AML population is fairly well constrained to\'a0
\f2\b 40-50%
\f1\b0 \'a0regardless of reasonable demographic assumptions. It's not a sensitive parameter. Varying it from 40% to 50% only moves your aggregate \uc0\u960  by a couple of percentage points, which is much less uncertainty than your other assumptions like the cure fraction conditional on response.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

