\f2\b \cf2 The two-step structure
\f1\b0 \

\f2\b Step 1 \'97 Who responds immunologically?
\f1\b0 \
This is the probability that a given patient mounts a meaningful T-cell response to GPS. It has two parallel routes:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 CD8+ route (requires HLA-A*02:01+):\
  P(CD8 response) = P(HLA-A*02:01+) \'d7 P(response | HLA+)\
                  = 0.45 \'d7 0.86\
                  = ~39% of the trial population\
\
CD4+ route (broadly HLA permissive):\
  P(CD4 response) = P(long peptide processing works) \'d7 P(response)\
                  = broadly available \'d7 ~44-57%\
                  = ~40-50% of the trial population\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 Some patients get both simultaneously \'97 particularly HLA-A*02:01+ patients who mount responses via all four peptides at once. That overlap is important.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 Step 2 \'97 Of responders, who gets cured?
\f1\b0 \
This is where Figure 5 comes in. The Phase 2 KM plateau tells you that among immunologic responders, roughly\'a0
\f2\b 57.5%
\f1\b0 \'a0appear to achieve durable remission \'97 that's your empirical cure fraction conditional on response.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 P(cured) = P(responds) \'d7 P(cured | responds)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 Why both CD4+ and CD8+ matter together
\f1\b0 \
This is actually the key biological insight and why the vaccine was designed with four peptides instead of just one:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls53\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 CD8+ alone
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 you get cytotoxic killing of leukemic blasts, but the response tends to fade over time without help. Short-term tumor control but potentially not durable\
\ls53\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 CD4+ alone
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 you get helper T-cell activation but no direct killing mechanism\
\ls53\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 CD8+ and CD4+ together
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 CD4+ helper cells sustain the CD8+ memory response long-term. This is what produces the plateau in Figure 5 rather than just a temporary survival benefit\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 The Phase 2 paper made this explicit \'97 none of the CD4+ responders relapsed. That's the durability signal. The CD4+ response isn't killing anything directly, it's maintaining the immunological memory that keeps the CD8+ killing active over years.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

