\f1 \cf2 \strokec2 Really sharp catch \'97 but there's a subtle problem with that multiplication.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 Why you can't just do 0.55 \'d7 0.44
\f1\b0 \
The 44% CD4+ response rate (4/9 patients tested) came from the\'a0
\f2\b total population
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 it wasn't measured separately in HLA-A*02:01- patients only. So it already includes both HLA+ and HLA- patients mixed together.\
If you multiply 0.55 \'d7 0.44 you're treating 44% as if it were the HLA- specific response rate, but it isn't \'97 it's the blended rate across both groups.\
\

\f2\b What you'd actually need
\f1\b0 \
To do this cleanly you'd need the CD4+ response rate broken out by HLA status:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 P(CD4 response) = P(CD4 resp | HLA+) \'d7 P(HLA+)\
                + P(CD4 resp | HLA-) \'d7 P(HLA-)\
\
0.44 = P(CD4 resp | HLA+) \'d7 0.45\
     + P(CD4 resp | HLA-) \'d7 0.55\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 That's one equation with two unknowns \'97 you can't solve it without knowing at least one of the conditional rates separately.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 What the paper actually tells us
\f1\b0 \
The Phase 2 paper explicitly stated there was\'a0
\f2\b no clear correlation with HLA-DR subtype
\f1\b0 \'a0among CD4+ responders \'97 which is actually useful information. It suggests the CD4+ response rate is probably roughly similar across HLA subtypes, meaning:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 P(CD4 resp | HLA+) \uc0\u8776  P(CD4 resp | HLA-) \u8776  44%\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 If that's true then:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 P(CD4 response and HLA-) = P(CD4 resp | HLA-) \'d7 P(HLA-)\
                         \uc0\u8776  0.44 \'d7 0.55\
                         \uc0\u8776  24%\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 In this specific case your instinct was actually right \'97\'a0
\f2\b because the CD4+ response appears HLA-DR independent
\f1\b0 , multiplying 0.44 \'d7 0.55 is a reasonable approximation for the HLA-A*02:01- patients who mount a CD4+ response. The paper's statement that no HLA-DR correlation was seen is the key justification that makes that multiplication valid.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 So the revised second term becomes:
\f1\b0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 P(HLA-A*02:01-) \'d7 P(CD4 response) \'d7 P(cure | CD4 responder)\
= 0.55 \'d7 0.44 \'d7 P(cure | CD4 responder)\
= 0.242 \'d7 P(cure | CD4 responder)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 The remaining uncertainty is entirely in that last term \'97 what fraction of CD4-only responders achieve durable remission. And that's where the Phase 2 finding that\'a0
\f2\b none of the CD4+ responders relapsed
\f1\b0 \'a0becomes the key data point, even though n is tiny.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

