\f2\b \cf2 What it literally says
\f1\b0 \
4 out of 4 CD4+ responders did not relapse during the follow-up period. That's a 0% relapse rate in that subgroup, which implies a 100% cure fraction conditional on CD4+ response \'97 at least within the observation window.\
\

\f2\b But you can't just use 100%
\f1\b0 \
The problem is\'a0
\f2\b n=4
\f1\b0 . With 4 patients the 95% confidence interval on that 0% relapse rate is enormous:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 95% CI on 0 events in 4 patients:\
Upper bound \uc0\u8776  1 - (0.05)^(1/4) \u8776  1 - 0.473 \u8776  52.7%\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 Meaning the true relapse rate could plausibly be as high as ~53% and you'd still observe 0 relapses in 4 patients by chance. So the data is consistent with anything from a true cure fraction of ~47% all the way up to ~100%.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 What it does tell you directionally
\f1\b0 \
Even if you can't pin down the exact number, the observation is still highly informative:\
