\f1 \cf2 \strokec2 Short answer \'97\'a0
\f2\b I didn't really build enrollment at all
\f1\b0 . It's essentially invisible in the current model and that's actually a meaningful gap. Let me explain what I did and what's missing.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 What the current model assumes
\f1\b0 \
The model implicitly treats all patients as if they enrolled on\'a0
\f2\b day zero simultaneously
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 then projects survival curves forward from that point. There's no enrollment process modeled at all. The\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 n_patients=116
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0parameter just scales the expected event counts in the velocity chart:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs18 \cf6 \cb16 \strokec6 python\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 counts\cf18 \strokec18 .\cf15 \strokec15 append\cf18 \strokec18 (\cf15 \strokec15 n_patients * \cf18 \strokec18 (\cf15 \strokec15 s1 - s2\cf18 \strokec18 ))\cf15 \cb1 \strokec15 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 That's it. It multiplies the survival probability drop by n to get expected events per window, but it assumes everyone entered the trial at the same time.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 Why that matters
\f1\b0 \
In reality REGAL enrolled patients over time \'97 we know from the data it enrolled over roughly\'a0
\f2\b 2-3 years
\f1\b0 \'a0starting January 2020. This has several implications the current model ignores:\

\f2\b Calendar time vs follow-up time are different.
\f1\b0 \'a0A patient who enrolled in January 2020 has 6+ years of follow-up. A patient who enrolled in December 2022 has maybe 3 years. The event velocity chart should reflect this heterogeneity.\

\f2\b Events accumulate on a calendar timeline
\f1\b0 , not all starting from month zero simultaneously. That's why REGAL counts events as they occur in real time \'97 60 events by month 46, 72 events by month 58 \'97 those are calendar time anchors, not follow-up time anchors.\
\

\f2\b What a proper enrollment model would look like
\f1\b0 \
You'd add an enrollment distribution \'97 typically assumed to be roughly uniform or slightly ramping:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs18 \cf6 \cb16 \strokec6 python\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs21 \cf17 \cb16 \strokec17 def\cf15 \strokec15  \cf21 \strokec21 simulate_enrollment\cf18 \strokec18 (\cf15 \strokec15 n_patients\cf18 \strokec18 ,\cf15 \strokec15  start_month\cf18 \strokec18 ,\cf15 \strokec15  end_month\cf18 \strokec18 ):\cf15 \strokec15 \
    \cf22 \strokec22 # Uniform enrollment over the accrual period\cf15 \strokec15 \
    enrollment_times = np\cf18 \strokec18 .\cf15 \strokec15 random\cf18 \strokec18 .\cf15 \strokec15 uniform\cf18 \strokec18 (\cf15 \strokec15 start_month\cf18 \strokec18 ,\cf15 \strokec15  end_month\cf18 \strokec18 ,\cf15 \strokec15  n_patients\cf18 \strokec18 )\cf15 \strokec15 \
    \cf17 \strokec17 return\cf15 \strokec15  np\cf18 \strokec18 .\cf15 \strokec15 sort\cf18 \strokec18 (\cf15 \strokec15 enrollment_times\cf18 \strokec18 )\cf15 \cb1 \strokec15 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 Then for each patient their\'a0
\f2\b observed follow-up time
\f1\b0 \'a0is:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs18 \cf6 \cb16 \strokec6 python\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 calendar_cutoff = \cf20 \strokec20 72\cf15 \strokec15   \cf22 \strokec22 # months from trial start\cf15 \strokec15 \
follow_up_time = calendar_cutoff - enrollment_time\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 And their event time is drawn from the survival distribution:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs18 \cf6 \cb16 \strokec6 python\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs21 \cf17 \cb16 \strokec17 def\cf15 \strokec15  \cf21 \strokec21 sample_event_time\cf18 \strokec18 (\cf15 \strokec15 cure_fraction\cf18 \strokec18 ,\cf15 \strokec15  median_os\cf18 \strokec18 ,\cf15 \strokec15  shape\cf18 \strokec18 ):\cf15 \strokec15 \
    \cf17 \strokec17 if\cf15 \strokec15  np\cf18 \strokec18 .\cf15 \strokec15 random\cf18 \strokec18 .\cf15 \strokec15 uniform\cf18 \strokec18 ()\cf15 \strokec15  < cure_fraction\cf18 \strokec18 :\cf15 \strokec15 \
        \cf17 \strokec17 return\cf15 \strokec15  np\cf18 \strokec18 .\cf15 \strokec15 inf  \cf22 \strokec22 # cured patient never has event\cf15 \strokec15 \
    \cf17 \strokec17 else\cf18 \strokec18 :\cf15 \strokec15 \
        \cf22 \strokec22 # Draw from Weibull\cf15 \strokec15 \
        u = np\cf18 \strokec18 .\cf15 \strokec15 random\cf18 \strokec18 .\cf15 \strokec15 uniform\cf18 \strokec18 ()\cf15 \strokec15 \
        lam = weibull_lambda\cf18 \strokec18 (\cf15 \strokec15 median_os\cf18 \strokec18 ,\cf15 \strokec15  shape\cf18 \strokec18 )\cf15 \strokec15 \
        \cf17 \strokec17 return\cf15 \strokec15  lam * \cf18 \strokec18 (\cf15 \strokec15 -np\cf18 \strokec18 .\cf15 \strokec15 log\cf18 \strokec18 (\cf15 \strokec15 u\cf18 \strokec18 ))\cf15 \strokec15  ** \cf18 \strokec18 (\cf20 \strokec20 1\cf15 \strokec15 /shape\cf18 \strokec18 )\cf15 \cb1 \strokec15 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 A patient is censored if their event time exceeds their follow-up time.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 Why the current model still works for what we're doing
\f1\b0 \
For estimating survival curves and cure fractions the simultaneous enrollment assumption is fine \'97 KM curves are plotted against follow-up time from enrollment, not calendar time. The survival shape and plateau are the same regardless of when patients enrolled.\
Where it breaks down is the\'a0
\f2\b event count anchors
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 the 60 events at month 46 and 72 events at month 58 that the Reddit poster used. Those are calendar time counts, not follow-up time counts. To properly use those anchors to validate the model you'd need to simulate the actual enrollment timeline and count events as they'd accumulate on a calendar basis.\
\

\f2\b Want me to add that to the Python model?
\f1\b0 \
It would mean adding a Monte Carlo simulation layer on top of the current analytical model \'97 simulate say 10,000 trial runs with realistic enrollment, draw event times from the survival distributions, and count calendar-time events to compare against the SEC filing anchors. That's actually the most rigorous way to validate whether our cure fraction estimate is consistent with what REGAL has publicly reported.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

