\f1 \cf2 \strokec2 Great question \'97 and it reveals an important distinction in how the simulation works.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 The simulation doesn't stop at 80 events
\f1\b0 \
In the real trial, SELLAS stops unblinded monitoring and triggers the final analysis when the 80th event occurs. But in our simulation we just let every patient run to either their event time or the calendar cutoff \'97 we don't stop enrolling or stop counting at 80.\
So the simulation generates\'a0
\f2\b all events across the entire follow-up window
\f1\b0 \'a0for all patients, which can exceed 80. The 80 threshold is only used to find\'a0
\f3\i when
\f1\i0 \'a0the 80th event occurs \'97 not to cap the total.\
\

\f2\b Why the real trial stops at 80
\f1\b0 \
The 80 events is a\'a0
\f2\b pre-specified statistical information fraction
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 the number of events required for the log-rank test to have sufficient power to detect the target HR at the desired significance level. It's set in the statistical analysis plan before the trial starts based on:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21 \cf15 \cb16 \strokec15 n_events = (z_alpha + z_beta)\'b2 / (p_GPS \'d7 (1 - p_GPS) + p_BAT \'d7 (1 - p_BAT))\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 Once 80 events accumulate the statisticians have enough information to make the primary OS comparison with the planned power. Enrolling more patients or waiting longer won't change the final analysis \'97 the clock stops at event 80.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 What this means for interpreting Panel 2
\f1\b0 \
The cumulative event curves in Panel 2 keep going past 80 because we're plotting the full simulation. The red dashed line at 80 is just a marker showing\'a0
\f3\i when
\f1\i0 \'a0the final analysis would trigger \'97 everything above it is what happens after the trial effectively ends, which in reality you'd never observe unblinded.\
\

\f2\b The fix if you want the simulation to reflect reality more closely
\f1\b0 \
You could add a stopping rule \'97 once the 80th pooled event occurs, censor all remaining patients at that calendar time:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs18 \cf6 \cb16 \strokec6 python\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs21 \cf22 \cb16 \strokec22 # Find calendar time of 80th event\cf15 \strokec15 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf17 \strokec17 if\cf15 \strokec15  \cf19 \strokec19 len\cf18 \strokec18 (\cf15 \strokec15 event_calendar_times\cf18 \strokec18 )\cf15 \strokec15  >= \cf20 \strokec20 80\cf18 \strokec18 :\cf15 \strokec15 \
    cutoff_80 = event_calendar_times\cf18 \strokec18 [\cf20 \strokec20 79\cf18 \strokec18 ]\cf15 \strokec15   \cf22 \strokec22 # 0-indexed\cf15 \strokec15 \
    \cf22 \strokec22 # Recensor everyone after that point\cf15 \strokec15 \
    had_event = had_event & \cf18 \strokec18 (\cf15 \strokec15 calendar_event_times <= cutoff_80\cf18 \strokec18 )\cf15 \cb1 \strokec15 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 But for the purpose of validating against the anchor counts at months 46 and 58 \'97 which both occur\'a0
\f3\i before
\f1\i0 \'a0the 80th event in reality \'97 the current approach is fine. The anchors are the more important validation target.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

