\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 What it implies biologically
\f1\b0 \
Events are accumulating slower in the real trial than your model predicts. There are only a few ways that can happen:\

\f2\b 1 \'97 The cure fraction is higher than 26.2%
\f1\b0 \'a0More cured patients = fewer events overall = slower accumulation. This is the most interesting possibility \'97 it would mean the GPS arm is performing better than the bottom-up HLA estimate suggested.\

\f2\b 2 \'97 BAT patients are living longer than 11 months
\f1\b0 \'a0If the true BAT median OS is closer to 14-16 months, events on the control arm accumulate more slowly. Given that BAT now includes venetoclax and hypomethylating agents \'97 which weren't widely available when the historical 8-16mo range was established \'97 this is actually plausible.\

\f2\b 3 \'97 GPS non-cured patients are living longer than 20 months
\f1\b0 \'a0If the susceptible GPS subpopulation has a median OS closer to 28-35 months, that also delays events.\

\f2\b 4 \'97 Some combination of all three
\f1\b0 \
\

\f2\b How to find the implied parameters
\f1\b0 \
Look at Panel 6 \'97 the cure fraction sweep. Find where the blue line crosses the horizontal dashed line at 60 and where the orange line crosses 72. Those crossings tell you which \uc0\u960  value is actually consistent with the observed anchor counts, holding BAT and GPS mOS fixed.\
From the numbers we saw, the crossing probably happens somewhere around\'a0
\f2\b \uc0\u960  = 40-45%
\f1\b0 , which is substantially higher than our bottom-up estimate of 26%. That would be a meaningful signal \'97 it would suggest the GPS arm is performing better than even the optimistic scenario we modeled.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

