\f2\b \cf2 The two key fixes
\f1\b0 \

\f2\b 1 \'97 Sort before interpolating.
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 interp1d
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0requires monotonically increasing x values. Since the means\'a0
\f3\i decrease
\f1\i0 \'a0as \uc0\u960  increases (higher cure fraction = fewer events), you need to sort by ascending mean before interpolating. Without this you get a nonsense crossing point.\

\f2\b 2 \'97 Convert units consistently.
\f1\b0 \'a0The sweep stores cure fractions as decimals (0.05 to 0.45) but\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 cf_pct
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0converts them to percentages. The interpolation returns a percentage, so divide by 100 when storing\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 needed_cure_fraction
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0as a decimal for use everywhere else.\

\f2\b 3 \'97 Sweep runs first, Monte Carlo runs second.
\f1\b0 \'a0Your version had them in the wrong order \'97 you were deriving\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 needed_cure_fraction
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0from a sweep but then the main Monte Carlo was still using the old\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 cure_fraction
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0variable. Now the sweep always runs first and\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 needed_cure_fraction
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0is the single source of truth for everything downstream.\
